{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_017umpstfxaHy2pd3CPJNN1a","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012JXXmvJQXR9G6teWzxs9fS","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded from recommendations","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a straightforward filtering logic test. The failure is: the filter function doesn't correctly check the in_stock flag or isn't applied. A unit test with mocked products can catch this by verifying that products with in_stock=False are excluded from results. No external systems, DB queries, or non-determinism involved.","test_description":"Unit test the filter function with a mocked product list containing both in_stock=True and in_stock=False products. Verify that only in_stock=True products appear in the filtered results.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"User preference filter excludes explicitly blocked product categories","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Similar to behavior 1: a filtering logic test that verifies whether the algorithm checks the user.blocked_categories set. Can be tested at unit level with mocked products and user settings. The failure is logic error in category exclusion, not a data loading or persistence issue.","test_description":"Unit test with a mocked user that has blocked_categories=['Electronics', 'Home']. Verify that products in those categories are excluded from results, while products in other categories are included.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Ranking algorithm prioritizes products matching recent browsing patterns over unbrowsed products","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This tests the ranking/scoring logic with mocked browse history and products. If the algorithm is heuristic-based (weighted sum of signals), a unit test can verify ranking order. Risk: if the algorithm uses a real ML model for similarity scoring, that would require Agentic testing. Assuming a deterministic heuristic algorithm, unit-level testing suffices.","test_description":"Unit test the ranking algorithm with a mocked user who has browsed products in category 'Phones' and category 'Laptops'. Verify that products from those categories rank higher than products from unbrowsed categories with similar base scores.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Pagination returns correct page with stable ordering across repeated requests","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests pagination slicing logic and determinism. With a mocked sorted list of products, unit tests can verify that page N returns the correct slice and that requesting page N twice returns identical results. No external dependencies or non-determinism sources involved.","test_description":"Unit test pagination by calling get_page(page=2, size=10) twice on a mocked sorted list of 100 products. Verify both calls return products at indices 10-19 in identical order.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Algorithm surfaces at least one product from a category user hasn't browsed (serendipity requirement)","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests that the algorithm enforces a diversity constraint. Unit test can verify this by checking the output categories against the user's browse history. This is a logical constraint on algorithm output, not a data persistence or external system issue.","test_description":"Unit test with a mocked user who has only browsed category 'Electronics'. Call the recommendation function and verify that the returned top-N results include at least one product from a different category (e.g., 'Books', 'Sports').","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"New user with no history receives popularity-based recommendations instead of empty set","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests the fallback strategy for new users. Unit test with a new user (empty browse/purchase history) can verify that the algorithm returns popular products rather than empty results. This is algorithm logic, not a DB or external system concern.","test_description":"Unit test by calling the recommendation function with a new user (empty purchase_history, empty browse_history). Verify that results are returned and are ranked by a popularity metric, not empty.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Click tracking records correct product ID, position, and timestamp for each user click","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Click tracking implies data persistence for future training. A unit test of the logging function alone (mocking the DB call) would miss failures like: DB write failures, data corruption, timestamp generation errors, or the data not actually being persisted. Must test the full loop: click event → log to DB → verify data in DB. Requires Integration-level testing with a test database.","test_description":"Integration test with a test database. Simulate user click on product_id=42 at position=3. Query the click tracking collection and verify a record exists with product_id=42, position=3, and a timestamp within the last second.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"Response time for generating recommendations stays under 200ms for 100,000 product catalog","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Performance regression only appears at scale. A unit test with mocked 10 products would pass in microseconds but the real system would fail at 100k. Unit-level mocking cannot catch this failure. Must test with real-scale data (100k products) in a test database to exercise actual algorithmic complexity and DB query patterns.","test_description":"Integration test with a test database loaded with 100,000 products. Measure wall-clock time to generate recommendations for a typical user. Assert that response time is under 200ms. Run multiple times to ensure consistent performance.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"Purchased products are deprioritized in subsequent recommendation requests","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This tests the full feedback loop: purchase event must be recorded to DB, then subsequent ranking must reflect updated purchase history. Unit testing the ranking function with mocked purchase history would miss failures where: purchase events aren't being recorded, DB updates aren't reflected in queries, or ranking logic doesn't read purchase history correctly. Requires Integration testing with DB writes and reads.","test_description":"Integration test with test database. Get recommendations, parse top product, record it as purchased in DB, get recommendations again, verify the purchased product either doesn't appear or is ranked lower in the new results.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Recommendation results are deterministic for same user state","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests the algorithm's contract: identical input state should produce identical output. With mocked/deterministic dependencies, unit testing can verify this. However, if the algorithm depends on external, non-deterministic services (e.g., real ML APIs, randomness), unit mocks would hide that failure, requiring Integration/System testing. Assuming the algorithm is designed to be deterministic, unit testing is sufficient.","test_description":"Unit test by calling the recommendation function twice with identical user state (same browse_history, purchase_history, preferences, etc.) and mocked product data. Verify both calls return the same ranked product list in the same order.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.6,"Integration":0.3,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13567,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13567},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c9dd5e25-7bd3-4a34-bd22-7bad0e173894","uuid":"1203a56f-fed9-4660-b837-29e1d099ace8"}
